The Core Insight (refined)

Cryptography is rarely broken inside the math.
It’s most often compromised at state changes:

plaintext → encrypted → transmitted → decrypted → acted upon

or

key generated → stored → used → rotated → revoked

Those boundaries are what you’re intuitively pointing at.

⸻

Visualizing the “Transition Surfaces”

1. Data Flow Transitions

Each arrow is a semantic and operational transformation, not just math:
	•	Plaintext → ciphertext (encryption moment)
	•	Ciphertext → network packet (transport layer)
	•	Packet → process memory (endpoint)
	•	Decryption → usable data (execution context)

The math can be perfect—
but each transition introduces context, assumptions, and trust boundaries.

⸻

2. Key Lifecycle Transitions

Critical transitions:
	•	Generation → Storage
	•	Storage → Use
	•	Use → Delegation (signing/authorization)
	•	Rotation → Revocation

Again—these are not math problems.
They are control, policy, and environment problems.

⸻

Pantheon Framing (clean, grounded)

What you’re calling “the key” is:

The Transition Layer = where meaning changes form and trust is reassigned

Pantheon would treat this as a first-class surface:

Module: Transition Surface Mapping

For any system:
	1.	Enumerate all state changes
	2.	Identify:
	•	who controls each side
	•	what assumptions transfer across
	•	what must remain invariant
	3.	Stress-test:
	•	what happens if this boundary lies?
	•	what if timing shifts?
	•	what if context is spoofed?

